07531nam a22010095i 9783110743036DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021936926  a97831107430367 a10.1515/97831107430362doi  a(DE-B1597)577278  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aIntra-individual Variation in Language /ced. by Lars Bülow, Simone E. Pfenninger, Markus Schiegg, Alexander Werth. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (VI, 411 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Linguistics. Studies and Monographs [TiLSM] ;v36300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tWhat Is Intra-individual Variation in Language? -- tPart I: Phonetic-phonological dimension -- tEveryone Is Different, So Everyone Is the Same – Intra-individual Variation in Second Language Acquisition -- tSituational Effects on Intra-individual Variation in German – Reflexes of Middle High German ei in Austrian Speech Repertoires -- tLinguistic, Social, and Individual Factors Constraining Variation in Spoken Swiss Standard German -- tPart II: Syntactic-morphological dimension -- tIntra-individual Variation in Nominal Inflection: Analyses of Directly Elicited Data of the Bavarian Linguistic Atlas -- tIntra-individual Variation in Morphosyntax: A Constraint-based Perspective -- tInter- and Intra-individual Variation in Luxembourgish. A Quantitative Analysis of Crowd-sourced Speech Data -- tPart III: Historical dimension -- tOf Zibele and Bölle: Patterns of Language Variation in the Swiss Language Island New Glarus (North America) -- tIntra-individual Variation in Nineteenth-century Private Letters -- tIntra-individual Variation from a Historical Perspective: Towards a Usage-based Model of Constructional Change and Variation -- tHow many Natives with how many Systems? Intra-individual Variation and the Threshold of Multilingualism in Standard German Speakers -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume offers several empirical, methodological, and theoretical approaches to the study of observable variation within individuals on various linguistic levels. With a focus on German varieties, the chapters provide answers on the following questions (inter alia):Which linguistic and extra-linguistic factors explain intra-individual variation? Is there observable intra-individual variation that cannot be explained by linguistic and extra-linguistic factors? Can group-level results be generalised to individual language usage and vice versa? Is intra-individual variation indicative of actual patterns of language change? How can intra-individual variation be examined in historical data?Consequently, the various theoretical, methodological and empirical approaches in this volume offer a better understanding of the meaning of intra-individual variation for patterns of language development, language variation and change.The inter- and transdisciplinary nature of the volume is an exciting new frontier, and the results of the studies in this book provide a wealth of new findings as well as challenges to some of the existing findings and assumptions regarding the nature of intra-individual variation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aHistorische Sprachwissenschaft. 4aPsycholinguistik. 4aSoziolinguistik.  aGerman.  aLanguage Change.  aLanguage Variation.  aSociolinguistics.1 aAuer, Anita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBritain, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBüchler, Andrin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBülow, Lars, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary